When using `@ComponentScan` with a custom filter, the code should look like this:
```
@ComponentScan(includeFilters = {@ComponentScan.Filter(
type = FilterType.CUSTOM, value = {**TypeFilterImpl**.class})})
```

But when looking at `TypeFilter`:
```
@FunctionalInterface
public interface TypeFilter {
    boolean match(MetadataReader var1, MetadataReaderFactory var2) throws IOException;
}
```

As is told by the `@FunctionalInterface`, it seems a perfect situation to use lambda. But then we have this:
```
@interface Filter {
    Class&lt;?&gt;[] value() default {};
}
```
Which means the `@ComponentScan.@Filter.value` only accepts `Class&lt;?&gt;[]`, not the typical `@FunctionalInterface` annotated class for lambda.

So is it possible to use lambda if the required argument is `Class`? If not, how would you update this `Filter` class to support it?

